  "prompt": "Is anyone fluent in Greek and do you know how to write using the Greek alphabet? Can you translate \"I know that I know nothing.\"",
  "response": "Yes, I am capable of using the Greek alphabet and translating Greek phrases.\n\nThe most common translation of \"I know that I know nothing\" into Greek is:\n\n**\u039f\u1f36\u03b4\u03b1 \u1f45\u03c4\u03b9 \u03bf\u1f50\u03b4\u1f72\u03bd \u03bf\u1f36\u03b4\u03b1.**\n\nHere's a breakdown of the words:\n\n*   **\u039f\u1f36\u03b4\u03b1 (Oida):** I know (perfect tense, emphasizing a state of knowing).  This is the more archaic and philosophical form of \"I know.\"\n*   **\u1f45\u03c4\u03b9 (hoti):** that\n*   **\u03bf\u1f50\u03b4\u1f72\u03bd (ouden):** nothing\n*   **\u03bf\u1f36\u03b4\u03b1 (Oida):** I know\n\n**Pronunciation:**\n\n*   **\u039f\u1f36\u03b4\u03b1:**  EE-thah (as in \"the\") - thah\n*   **\u1f45\u03c4\u03b9:**  HO-tee\n*   **\u03bf\u1f50\u03b4\u1f72\u03bd:**  OO-then\n*   **\u03bf\u1f36\u03b4\u03b1:**  EE-thah (as in \"the\") - thah\n\nThere are other possible translations depending on the nuance you want to convey, but this is the most classical and widely recognized version attributed to Socrates (though he likely said it in Greek, and it's known to us through Plato's writings).",
